\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Hydrodynamic Synchronization of optically trapped micro-beads
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hydrodynamic interaction plays an important role in the dynamics of microscopic
 particles.
 In a simple experimental setup using two optical traps, trapping a microbead
 each, we study the response of the second bead when first bead is driven
 with periodic force.
 We have further developed a theory to study and analyzed the experimental
 results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The force balance equation of the optically trapped bead is,
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\backslash

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
\dot{\mathbf{R}_{i}} & =\mathbf{v}_{i}\\
m\dot{\mathbf{v}}_{i} & =-\bm{\gamma}_{ij}\mathbf{v}_{j}-\bm{\nabla}_{i}U+\bm{\xi}_{i}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the above Eq.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are position and velocity of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th particle of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\gamma}_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is manybody friction tensor and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is the potential and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 is noise of thermal origin.
 In a optical trap, the potential is 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $U(t)=\frac{1}{2}\sum k_{i}(\mathbf{R}_{i}-\mathbf{R}_{i}^{0})^{2}$
\end_inset


\series default
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}_{i}^{0}$
\end_inset

 is the position of the potential minimum of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th optical trap.
 In the experimental set up the minimum of the optical trap is shifting
 with a periodic signal from outside and the response of the two beads have
 been studied.
 Assuming momentum to be rapidly relaxing on the time scale of the trap
 motion, we neglect inertia and average over the noise to get,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
-\bm{\gamma}_{ij}\mathbf{\dot{R}}_{j} & -\bm{\nabla}_{i}U=0
\end{alignat}

\end_inset

Eq.(2) can be inverted and presented in terms of mobility matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\mu}_{ij}=\bm{\gamma}_{ij}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 as,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\negthickspace\negthickspace\mathbf{\dot{R}}_{1} & = & -\mu k_{1}\bm{\delta}(\mathbf{R}_{1}-\mathbf{R}_{1}^{0})-\bm{\mu}_{12}k_{2}(\mathbf{R}_{2}-\mathbf{R}_{2}^{0})\nonumber \\
\negthickspace\negthickspace\mathbf{\dot{R}}_{2} & = & -\bm{\mu}_{21}k_{1}(\mathbf{R}_{1}-\mathbf{R}_{1}^{0})-\mu k_{2}\bm{\delta}(\mathbf{R}_{2}-\mathbf{R}_{2}^{0})
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we introduce new variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\Delta}_{i}=\mathbf{R}_{i}-\mathbf{R}_{i}^{0}$
\end_inset

, approximate mobility matrices with separation vector to be the average
 distance between two minimum of the optical traps.
 Thus we get,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\negthickspace\frac{d}{dt}\left[\begin{array}{c}
\bm{\Delta}_{1}\\
\bm{\Delta}_{2}
\end{array}\right]=-\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\mu k_{1}\bm{\delta} & \bm{\mu}_{12}k_{2}\\
\bm{\mu}_{21}k_{1} & \mu k_{2}\bm{\delta}
\end{array}\right]\negthickspace\left[\begin{array}{c}
\bm{\Delta}_{1}\\
\bm{\Delta}_{2}
\end{array}\right]\negthickspace-\negthickspace\left[\begin{array}{c}
\dot{\mathbf{R}}_{1}^{0}\\
\dot{\mathbf{R}}_{2}^{0}
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Steady state solution of the Eq.(4) can easily be calculated by taking Fourier
 transformation.
 Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\mu k_{1}\bm{\delta} & \bm{\mu}_{12}k_{2}\\
\bm{\mu}_{21}k_{1} & \mu k_{2}\bm{\delta}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

, the solution in frequency is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bm{\Delta}_{i}(\omega)=i\omega[-i\omega\bm{\delta}+\mathbf{A}]_{ij}^{-1}\mathbf{R}_{j}^{0}(\omega)=\bm{\chi}_{ij}(\omega)\mathbf{R}_{j}^{0}(\omega)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which defines the response for 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\chi}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the minimum of the optical trap is modulated by a sinusoidal wave with
 driving frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{R}_{j}^{0}(\omega)=\frac{\mathbf{X}_{i}}{2}(\delta(\omega-\Omega)+\delta(\omega+\Omega)).$
\end_inset

 Further 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\chi}$
\end_inset

 is a block-diagonal matrix in cartesian indices.
 Given the experimental set up 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\chi}$
\end_inset

 can be decomposed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\chi}_{\parallel}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bm{\chi}_{\perp}$
\end_inset

for motion along the trap separation and the motion perpendicular to it.
 Inserting this form of the signal into the Eq.
 above and taking the response equation back to time domain, we find
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta_{\parallel i}(t)=\chi_{\parallel ij}'(\Omega)\cos(\Omega t)X_{j}+\chi_{\parallel ij}''(\Omega)\sin(\Omega t)X_{j}
\]

\end_inset

Two time scales from two traps can be calculated to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{i}=1/\mu k_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Float figure
wide true
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename chi11.eps
	display false
	width 105text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename chi21.eps
	display false
	width 105text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Real and imaginary part of the response function(a).
 Cole-Cole plot (b) and the amplitude of the response function.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{widetext}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\bm{\chi}_{\parallel}(\Omega) & = & i\Omega\left[\begin{array}{cc}
(\mu k_{1}-i\Omega) & \mu_{12}k_{2}\\
\\
\mu_{21}k_{1} & (\mu k_{2}-i\Omega)
\end{array}\right]^{-1}=\frac{i\Omega}{Det\, A_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2}-i\Omega Tr\, A_{\parallel}}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
(\mu k_{2}-i\Omega) & -\mu_{21}k_{1}\\
\, & \,\\
-\mu_{12}k_{2} & (\mu k_{1}-i\Omega)
\end{array}\right]\\
\\
\bm{\chi}_{\parallel}^{'}(\Omega) & = & \frac{\Omega^{2}}{(Det\, A_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2})^{2}+\Omega^{2}(Tr\, A_{\parallel})^{2}}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
{\displaystyle Det\, A_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2}-\mu k_{2}Tr\, A_{\parallel}} & {\displaystyle \mu_{21}k_{1}Tr\, A_{\parallel}}\\
\\
{\displaystyle \mu_{12}k_{2}Tr\, A_{\parallel}} & {\displaystyle Det\, A_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2}-\mu k_{1}Tr\, A_{\parallel}}
\end{array}\right]\\
\\
\bm{\chi}_{\parallel}^{''}(\Omega) & = & \frac{\Omega}{(Det\, A_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2})^{2}+\Omega^{2}(Tr\, A_{\parallel})^{2}}\left[\begin{array}{cc}
{\displaystyle \mu k_{2}(Det\, A_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2})+\Omega^{2}Tr\, A_{\parallel}} & {\displaystyle -\mu_{21}k_{1}(Det\, A_{\parallel}}-\Omega^{2})\\
\\
-{\displaystyle \mu_{12}k_{2}(Det\, A_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2})} & {\displaystyle \mu k_{1}(Det\, A_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2})+\Omega^{2}Tr\, A}_{\parallel}
\end{array}\right]
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{widetext}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are interested in the resonance in amplitude of the second bead due to
 the forcing of the first bead, that is given by the maximising modulus
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{\parallel21}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
|\chi_{21}| & =\big| & \frac{-i\Omega\mu_{12}k_{2}}{Det\, A_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2}-i\Omega Tr\, A_{\parallel}}\big|\\
 & = & \frac{\Omega\mu_{12}k_{2}}{\sqrt{\left(Det\, A_{\parallel}-\Omega^{2}\right)^{2}+\Omega^{2}(Tr\, A_{\parallel})^{2}}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly the resonance frequency in dimensionless unit is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}\Omega_{res}=\sqrt{\frac{DetA_{\parallel}}{\mu^{2}k_{1}^{2}}}=\sqrt{\frac{k_{2}}{k_{1}}\left(1-\frac{\mu_{\parallel12}^{2}}{\mu^{2}}\right)}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_{12}\neq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can further calculate auto-correlation and cross-correlation functions.
 To do that, we have kept two separate particles in two different optical
 traps and let them jiggle due to the thermal motion.
 The equation of motion for such motion is described by,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\negthickspace\frac{d}{dt}\left[\begin{array}{c}
\bm{\Delta}_{1}\\
\bm{\Delta}_{2}
\end{array}\right]=-\left[\begin{array}{cc}
\mu k_{1}\bm{\delta} & \bm{\mu}_{12}k_{2}\\
\bm{\mu}_{21}k_{1} & \mu k_{2}\bm{\delta}
\end{array}\right]\negthickspace\left[\begin{array}{c}
\bm{\Delta}_{1}\\
\bm{\Delta}_{2}
\end{array}\right]\negthickspace+\negthickspace\left[\begin{array}{c}
\bm{\xi}_{1}\\
\bm{\xi}_{2}
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Writing this equation in index form we get,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\dot{\Delta}_{i}=-A_{ij}\Delta_{j}+B_{ij}w_{j}
\]

\end_inset

 where noise is correlated Wiener processes with variances go as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}\mathbf{B}^{T}=k_{b}T\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 and white noise 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle w\rangle=0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle w_{i}(t)w_{j}(t')\rangle=\delta_{ij}\delta(t-t')$
\end_inset

.
 The solution of this multivariate Stochatic differential equation is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bm{\Delta}(t)=\bm{\Delta}(0)e^{-\mathbf{A}t}+\int_{0}^{t}ds\, e^{-\mathbf{A}(t-s)}\mathbf{B}\mathbf{w}
\]

\end_inset

 Keeping the particles in the trap for long time will let them equilibriate
 and all transient effect will die out and hence will not have any consequences.
 The correlation matrix can be calculated which will only depend on contribution
 from noise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bm{\Delta}(t)\bm{\Delta}^{T}(t')=\int_{0}^{t'}\int_{0}^{t}ds'ds\, e^{-\mathbf{A}(t-s)}\mathbf{B}\mathbf{w}\mathbf{w}^{T}\mathbf{B}^{T}e^{-\mathbf{A}^{T}(t'-s')}.
\]

\end_inset

For stationary case average of the correlator become,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{widetext}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\langle\bm{\Delta}(t)\bm{\Delta}^{T}(t')\rangle_{eq} & = & \int_{-\infty}^{t'}\int_{-\infty}^{t}ds'ds\, e^{-\mathbf{A}(t-s)}\mathbf{B}\langle\mathbf{w}\mathbf{w}^{T}\rangle_{eq}\mathbf{B}^{T}e^{-\mathbf{A}^{T}(t'-s')}.\\
\langle\bm{\Delta}(t)\bm{\Delta}^{T}(t')\rangle_{eq} & = & e^{-\mathbf{A}(t-t')}\int_{-\infty}^{t}ds\, e^{-\mathbf{A}(t'-s)}\mathbf{B}\mathbf{B}^{T}e^{-\mathbf{A}^{T}(t'-s)}=e^{-\mathbf{A}(t-t')}\mathbf{C}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{widetext}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{C}$
\end_inset

 is the stationary covariance matrix, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a two dimensional system C can easily be calculated 
\backslash
cite{gardinar}, the solution is 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{C}=\frac{(Det\,\mathbf{A})\mathbf{B}\mathbf{B}^{T}+[\mathbf{A}-Tr\,\mathbf{A}]\mathbf{B}\mathbf{B}^{T}[\mathbf{A}-Tr\,\mathbf{A}]}{2Tr\,\mathbf{A}\, Det\,\mathbf{A}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_body
